{{nihongo|'''''Dokuo'''''|毒男||literally "poison man"}} is a Japanese slang term for single males, which originates on the [[2channel]] internet textboard.<ref name="netyougo">{{cite web |url= http://netyougo.com/2ch/3153.html|title= 毒男|trans-title=Dokuo|work= ネット用語の辞典サイト「ネット王子」|publisher= Netyougo|location= Japan|language= Japanese|archiveurl= |archivedate= |accessdate= 17 May 2014}}</ref><ref name="livedoor20100501">{{cite web |url= http://news.livedoor.com/article/detail/4742058/ |first= Setsuko |last=Saeda |title= 恋愛弱者の男たち、「毒男」「孤男」「喪男」って実際どうなの？|trans-title=What's the truth behind "dokuo" and "moo" guys left behind in the love race? |date= 1 May 2010|work= Peachy News |publisher= Line Corporation|location= Japan|language= Japanese|archiveurl= |archivedate= |accessdate= 17 May 2014}}</ref> The term derives from the Japanese {{Nihongo||独身男|dokushin otoko}}<ref name="netyougo"/> or {{Nihongo||独身男性|dokushin dansei}}.<ref name="livedoor20100501"/>

The Chinese song "Love and Honesty" mentions ''dokuo''.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wh7TLodE4ok |title= [高登膠歌]毒男 (原曲：愛與誠) |date=July 29, 2009 | accessdate = April 11, 2013|language=Chinese}}</ref>

