{{Pashto language sidebar}}

'''Kandahārī Pashtō''' ({{lang-ps|کندهارۍ پښتو}}), also known as '''Southern Pashto''', '''Western Pashto''', or '''Southwestern Pashto''',<ref>Prods Oktor Skjærvø, P.O. 1989. Pashto. In "Compendium Linguarum Iranicarum", R. Schmitt (ed.), 384-410.</ref> is a [[Pashto dialects|Pashto dialect]], spoken in southern and western [[Afghanistan]], including the city of [[Kandahar]]. It is similar with Quetta (Kakar) and Khattak dialects (95–100% similarities in vocabulary, and 80% with [[Yusufzai (Peshawari) Pashto|Yusufzai dialect]]). It is one of the most archaic and most prestigious varieties of [[Pashto language|Pashto]].

Kandahari Pashto is spoken in [[Kandahar Province|Kandahar]], [[Helmand Province|Helmand]], [[Ghazni]],  most of [[Urozgan Province|Urozgan]], [[Farah Province|Farah]], and [[Nimruz Province|Nimruz]], [[Shinkot|southeastern]] [[Ghor Province|Ghor]], the districts of [[Murghab District|Murghab]], [[Ghormach District|Ghormach]], [[Muqur District, Badghis|Muqur]], and [[Jawand District|Jawand]] in [[Badghis Province|Badghis]], and parts of [[Zabul Province|Zabul]], [[Paktika Province|Paktika]], and [[Herat Province|Herat]] provinces of Afghanistan. It is also spoken in parts of the provinces of [[Razavi Khorasan]] and [[South Khorasan]] in [[Iran]], where they numbered roughly 120,000 (in 1993).<ref>https://www.ethnologue.com/country/ir/languages</ref> Kandahari Pashto is almost same as the southeastern Pashto dialect, spoken in northern Balochistan including [[Quetta]] city, except for few phonetic differences.

The Kandahari dialect retains archaic retroflex [[Sibilant consonant|sibilants]], {{IPA|/ʂ/}} and {{IPA|/ʐ/}} (in other dialects, they have shifted to ʃ/x and ʒ/g). In the Quetta and Kakar dialects they change to ʃ and ʒ. Kandahari also has the affricates {{IPA|/t͡s/}} and {{IPA|/d͡z/}}.
